# Auth and service context

The `service` struct has `Acc` (Account), `Member`, and `Workspace`. Many handlers use `s.Acc.Name` (and similar) for `lastModifiedByName` / `createdByName`. If a request is authenticated via a path that does **not** set `s.Acc`, those handlers will panic (nil pointer or equivalent).

## Rule

**Any auth middleware that calls `SetWorkspaceObject` and `SetMemberObject` must also call `SetAccountObject`** with a valid (possibly synthetic) Account when downstream handlers perform writes that use `s.Acc`.

## Example (RequireAPIKey)

```go
// ✅ Correct: API key auth sets workspace, member, AND account
s.SetWorkspaceObject(ws)
s.SetMemberObject(&Member{WorkspaceID: ws.ID})
s.SetAccountObject(&Account{Name: "Claude (API)"})
```

If you add a new auth path (e.g. another API key or machine auth), set all three. If you add a new handler under an existing auth path, ensure that path sets `s.Acc` before any code that uses `s.Acc.Name`, `s.Acc.ID`, etc.

## Where it matters

Handlers that use `s.Acc` include: feature/description update, status, annotations, create feature, move, comments, and most other write operations in `service.go`. Read-only handlers (e.g. get projects, get features) may not need it.
